y psychogeography’s interest in ‘hidden histories’ and haunted places to spaces associated with ‘wilderness’ and ‘the countryside’. Kathleen Jamie’s allusions to the Gothic are put in relation to her feminist re-writing of ‘the outdoors’, and John Burnside’s use of haunting is shown to dismantle fictions of ‘the far north’. This book provides not only a discussion of a wide range of factual and fictional narratives of the present but also an analysis of the intertextual dialogue with the Romantic tradition which enfolds in these texts.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEnglish literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGhosts in literature. 0aNatural history literaturezGreat BritainxHistory. 0aNature in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  a21st-century literature.  aNature writing.  ahaunting.  aspace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831106786420 cprintz978311067859840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311067861140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110678611423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/co